#- The Iron Home§0
§0-An idea from§0
§0SexyBunny§0
§0
§0Gerold was getting§0
§0tired. He had walked a§0
§0long way. He thought§0
§0back to home, and the§0
§0countless hours he§0
§0had spent mining iron§0
§0to reinforce it. He§0
§0remembered the walls§0
§0of cobble and oak,§0

#- the netherrack fire in§0
§0the hearth. All the§0
§0hours he spent§0
§0working on it. It made§0
§0him happy to know that§0
§0there was something to§0
§0be proud of in the§0
§0bleak world of§0
§0Civcraft, his own§0
§0creations were his§0
§0greatest pride.§0
§0Bounding over hills,§0
§0Gerold thought
#- about§0

#- how far away he was§0
§0from home. He knew§0
§0that it was just over§0
§0the next lot of hills.§0
§0Bounding with pride§0
§0and joy, Gerold looked§0
§0over the hills to see a§0
§0magnificent sight.§0
§0There, resting infront§0
§0of the setting sun, was§0
§0his house. He was§0
§0home.§0
§0THE
#- END.§0

#- The Diamond Ground§0
§0-A Novel by§0
§0Mr_Tommytoms§0
§0
§0Dig. Dig. Dig Right. Dig§0
§0Left. Oh god, why can't§0
§0I find these Diamonds?!§0
§0The thought of going§0
§0away from this mining§0
§0trip empty handed was§0
§0a distressing thought§0
§0to Tom. He'd been§0
§0mining for 3 hours
#- 

#- straight, and yet he§0
§0still hasn't found§0
§0anything except coal.§0
§0Muttering under his§0
§0breath Tom said, "I§0
§0swear to TTK2, if I§0
§0don't find any§0
§0Diamonds, I'll be so§0
§0pissed". Breaking the§0
§0fragile stone walls,§0
§0Tom wondered about§0
§0the glistening gem that§0
§0is a §0

#- diamond. Suddenly, with§0
§0a pop, the stone broke§0
§0off to reveal a§0
§0beautiful cavern§0
§0stretching vast§0
§0distances as far as§0
§0the render distance§0
§0can see. Out of the§0
§0corner of Tom's eye,§0
§0he could see§0
§0something glistening.§0
§0Turning his head ever§0
§0so slowly, revealed
#- 

#- the most glorious thing§0
§0he'd seen in ages. A§0
§0vein of diamonds, ripe§0
§0for the mining!§0
§0Changing his hotbar§0
§0slot to his Silk touch§0
§0iron pick, Tom began§0
§0his sprint to the§0
§0Diamonds. Ten metres§0
§0were all that was§0
§0between the diamonds§0
§0and Tom. Running§0
§0faster,
#- Tom §0

#- could nearly touch the§0
§0diamonds! Tripping on a§0
§0stray rock, that was§0
§0the last Tom saw of§0
§0those Diamonds. He fell§0
§0down an unseen hole,§0
§0where the scorching§0
§0lava burned him up,§0
§0destroying him and all§0
§0of his possesions. §0
§0Some say that to this§0
§0day, Tom's
#- ghost §0

#- still haunts that§0
§0particular vein of§0
§0diamonds, scratching§0
§0at the rocks, knowing§0
§0deep down that there§0
§0is nothing he can do to§0
§0get his diamonds... all§0
